    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-01-10T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-01-10T23:00:00-05:00" n="875"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d875">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.6363/305: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-01-11T13:00:00+09:00"
                            >January 11, 1937—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 11—6:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4. Embassy’s 3, January 8, 7 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>In Dickover’s talk on Saturday morning with Matsushima, Chief of the
                        Commercial Bureau of the Foreign Office, the latter agreed with apparent
                        sincerity that it was out of the question for the foreign oil companies
                        either to invest further money in Japan or to guarantee an adequate return
                        to Mitsui when their future was so uncertain as was indicated by the latest
                        developments in the Japan and Korea quotas. He said that the Minister for
                        Foreign Affairs had asked him to take up with the Ministry of Commerce and
                        Industry the whole problem of the foreign oil interests in Japan and that
                            Arita<note n="31" xml:id="d875fn31">Hachiro Arita, Japanese Minister for
                            Foreign Affairs.</note> was pressing him almost daily to persuade that
                        Ministry to seek an early adjustment of the situation by meeting in some
                        degree the reasonable requirements of the foreign oil companies. The
                        impression received by Dickover is that our representations of December <pb
                            facs="0733" n="725" xml:id="pg_725"/> 24<note n="32" xml:id="d875fn32"
                            >See Embassy’s telegram No. 268, December 24, 1936, 6 p.m., <ref
                                target="frus1936v04#pg_805">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1936, vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 805</ref>.</note> have fallen on
                        good ground, at least so far as the Foreign Office is concerned, and that
                        Arita is genuinely disturbed at the situation of the oil companies.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Sansom in his talk with Matsushima also received the distinct impression
                        that the Foreign Office is sympathetic to the plight of the oil
                        companies.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
